1
00:00:00,690 --> 00:00:07,500
Let me share my biggest struggles when I first
started trading: I had very little self-control

2
00:00:07,500 --> 00:00:13,460
and I was unable to resist the temptation
to over-trade and over-leverage.

3
00:00:13,460 --> 00:00:17,900
If you’re in your first years, you’re
probably facing the same issues.

4
00:00:17,900 --> 00:00:23,220
So today I want to reveal the several tweaks
I’ve made to save my trading.

5
00:00:23,220 --> 00:00:26,912
So, like, subscribe, and stick around for
the full video.

6
00:00:26,912 --> 00:00:33,739
“High" tends to indicate even higher and
"low" usually means even lower

7
00:00:33,739 --> 00:00:38,910
There is a special appeal to trade against
the trend or against a big momentum price

8
00:00:38,910 --> 00:00:39,910
move.

9
00:00:39,910 --> 00:00:43,559
The main reason is the illusion of an "attractive"
price.

10
00:00:43,559 --> 00:00:49,460
A market that has been going down for many
days, by definition is going to have a relatively

11
00:00:49,460 --> 00:00:50,460
"low" price.

12
00:00:50,460 --> 00:00:54,910
And you’re tempted to buy it, at this low
price.

13
00:00:54,910 --> 00:01:01,530
The danger of these seemingly attractive prices
is an important law of trading: continuation

14
00:01:01,530 --> 00:01:04,110
is more likely than change.

15
00:01:04,110 --> 00:01:11,180
From my experience and many losing trades,
"high" tends to indicate even higher and "low"

16
00:01:11,180 --> 00:01:14,940
usually means even lower.

17
00:01:14,940 --> 00:01:20,500
This was one of my biggest mistakes: I took
far too many trades against a powerful price

18
00:01:20,500 --> 00:01:21,500
move.

19
00:01:21,500 --> 00:01:26,000
I haven’t kept records from the beginning,
but I’ve definitively lost far more money

20
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:27,541
on these trades than I’ve made.

21
00:01:27,541 --> 00:01:30,549
And it’s probably true for you.

22
00:01:30,549 --> 00:01:36,770
But, even more damaging than the amount lost
against these momentum moves were the profits

23
00:01:36,770 --> 00:01:42,520
not realized, because I’ve missed several
good trades with-the-trend.

24
00:01:42,520 --> 00:01:48,030
Trading against the trend will misdirect your
focus, and as a result you’ll miss many

25
00:01:48,030 --> 00:01:55,390
entry points for profitable trades in the
direction of the main trend.

26
00:01:55,390 --> 00:01:58,780
Against-the-trend trading has a tendency to
be addictive.

27
00:01:58,780 --> 00:02:00,939
And this will bring other problems.

28
00:02:00,939 --> 00:02:06,530
When a trade against-the-trend goes against
you, you’ll initally say: I was a little

29
00:02:06,530 --> 00:02:08,160
"early" with my timing.

30
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:14,780
And, there is a strong temptation to try again
and buy or sell more at what now has become

31
00:02:14,780 --> 00:02:17,739
an even "more attractive" price.

32
00:02:17,739 --> 00:02:22,190
So never add to a loser if it is against the
trend.

33
00:02:22,190 --> 00:02:27,160
My mentor had a funny saying: if you think
you reached the bottom of the ocean, and you

34
00:02:27,160 --> 00:02:31,739
can’t go lower, remember that you can always
dig the ground.

35
00:02:31,739 --> 00:02:33,390
The same with trading.

36
00:02:33,390 --> 00:02:38,140
If you think the market reached an absolute
high and it can’t go any higher, you’ll

37
00:02:38,140 --> 00:02:40,000
have a big surprise.

38
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:48,069
Your time span and your level of patience
When you trade, you need to know what the

39
00:02:48,069 --> 00:02:51,620
"time span" you will most often act upon.

40
00:02:51,620 --> 00:02:56,659
If you are a short-term trader and find it
difficult or impossible to hold positions

41
00:02:56,659 --> 00:03:03,230
for several days and instead get in and out
frequently, then you have to adjust your trading

42
00:03:03,230 --> 00:03:05,190
style accordingly.

43
00:03:05,190 --> 00:03:10,670
If you are swing trader and hold trades for
longer periods, regardless of short-term price

44
00:03:10,670 --> 00:03:16,780
movement, then you need to use a trading strategy
to capitalize on these tendencies.

45
00:03:16,780 --> 00:03:19,060
You need to know your patience level.

46
00:03:19,060 --> 00:03:24,170
If you know you are patient, then you’ll
be able to endure the inevitable fluctuations

47
00:03:24,170 --> 00:03:26,069
in your swing trades.

48
00:03:26,069 --> 00:03:31,000
If you know you are impatient, you’ll end
up trading shorter timeframes.

49
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:36,560
The shorter the timeframe you decide to trade,
the more intense concentration you will need

50
00:03:36,560 --> 00:03:37,680
to sustain.

51
00:03:37,680 --> 00:03:44,549
So, if we consider once again trading against
the trend, the only possible way to succeed

52
00:03:44,549 --> 00:03:50,180
is to be a short-term trader, as well as be
very selective (I mean only entering when

53
00:03:50,180 --> 00:03:52,550
momentum is clearly in your favor).

54
00:03:52,550 --> 00:03:59,459
And one of the worst trading styles is to
be a long-term swing trader who trades against

55
00:03:59,459 --> 00:04:01,329
strong trends.

56
00:04:01,329 --> 00:04:05,930
This combination will inevitably result in
consistent, big losses.

57
00:04:05,930 --> 00:04:11,260
So know your time span and your level of patience.

58
00:04:11,260 --> 00:04:17,169
Become a market specialist

59
00:04:17,169 --> 00:04:22,350
The first decision to make when designing
your strategy is to decide which currency

60
00:04:22,350 --> 00:04:28,230
pairs, cryptocurrencies or stocks you will
be trading, because, I said it many times

61
00:04:28,230 --> 00:04:33,520
before, not all strategies will work on every
market.

62
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:39,820
Trading price action on Tesla is very different
compared to Bitcoin’s price action.

63
00:04:39,820 --> 00:04:44,840
If you’re in your first years, it’s better
to become a market specialist.

64
00:04:44,840 --> 00:04:49,190
And as a specialist, you will concentrate
on one market.

65
00:04:49,190 --> 00:04:53,300
I have a friend which trades only one market,
GBPUSD.

66
00:04:53,300 --> 00:04:58,449
I know him for 10 years, and he never traded
anything else.

67
00:04:58,449 --> 00:05:04,080
It sounds radical, and but this works for
him, trading just one currency pair.

68
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:09,100
This comes with the understanding of the market,
knowing the factors that affect the market,

69
00:05:09,100 --> 00:05:15,669
and, of course, a solid strategy for different
phases of the market.

70
00:05:15,669 --> 00:05:21,120
When you are focusing on one market, you’ll
also learn the correlations associated with

71
00:05:21,120 --> 00:05:29,660
that market, when the market is reacting in
an unusual way, when is trending or not.

72
00:05:29,660 --> 00:05:35,919
If it’s too radical for you, monitoring
just one market, have a maximum of 3 markets

73
00:05:35,919 --> 00:05:37,440
and make them your focus.

74
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:41,410
If you have a hard time trading, try narrowing
down.

75
00:05:41,410 --> 00:05:43,120
It might help you.

76
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:48,639
Weekly maximum drawdown – best tool to avoid
overtrading

77
00:05:48,639 --> 00:05:52,390
Do you have a weekly maximum drawdown?

78
00:05:52,390 --> 00:05:53,550
You should!

79
00:05:53,550 --> 00:05:57,520
This is the amount you are willing to lose
over a period of time.

80
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:04,010
An easy way to measure the maximum drawdown
is to look at it during one trading week.

81
00:06:04,010 --> 00:06:08,069
You may risk 1 percent of your account on
each trade.

82
00:06:08,069 --> 00:06:14,130
If you set your weekly maximum drawdown to
5 percent, then you can withstand five losing

83
00:06:14,130 --> 00:06:16,590
trades in a row.

84
00:06:16,590 --> 00:06:21,750
After five losing trades, you have hit your
maximum drawdown for the week.

85
00:06:21,750 --> 00:06:26,490
This is when you stop trading for that week
because you reached your maximum drawdown.

86
00:06:26,490 --> 00:06:33,319
This is the best way to avoid over trading,
revenge trading and over leveraging.

87
00:06:33,319 --> 00:06:40,780
Now, how you decide to apply the maximum drawdown
rule may depend on the timeframe you decide

88
00:06:40,780 --> 00:06:42,530
to trade.

89
00:06:42,530 --> 00:06:48,210
If you are a scalper or an active day trader,
you may need a maximum drawdown amount for

90
00:06:48,210 --> 00:06:49,620
one day.

91
00:06:49,620 --> 00:06:54,889
That maximum drawdown will affect how many
trades you’ll be able to take at any given

92
00:06:54,889 --> 00:06:56,460
time.

93
00:06:56,460 --> 00:07:02,340
For example, you may decide to have a maximum
drawdown of 5 percent for each trading week.

94
00:07:02,340 --> 00:07:09,470
But If you have six daily signals on the first
trading day of the week, and you risk 1 percent

95
00:07:09,470 --> 00:07:14,990
on each trade, you could have a drawdown of
6 percent in your first day!

96
00:07:14,990 --> 00:07:21,110
So to avoid reaching your maximum weekly drawdown
on your first day, you should reduce your

97
00:07:21,110 --> 00:07:22,150
risk.

98
00:07:22,150 --> 00:07:28,560
Instead of risking 1 percent per trade, you
risk 0.5 percent per trade, or even lower.

99
00:07:28,560 --> 00:07:34,090
Find the balance between anticipation and
confirmation

100
00:07:34,090 --> 00:07:40,979
A popular concept in trading is to wait for
confirmation before entering a trade.

101
00:07:40,979 --> 00:07:46,069
This means you have a signal, for example,
a price action pattern, and you wait for the

102
00:07:46,069 --> 00:07:50,330
markets to confirm that pattern before you
enter.

103
00:07:50,330 --> 00:07:55,960
The idea, of course, is to filter out bad
trades and to gain confidence before entering

104
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:58,129
the trade.

105
00:07:58,129 --> 00:08:02,409
When planning a trade, there are two basic
approaches.

106
00:08:02,409 --> 00:08:06,879
You can anticipate a move or you can wait
for confirmation.

107
00:08:06,879 --> 00:08:11,280
Both methods have their pros and cons.

108
00:08:11,280 --> 00:08:16,419
Anticipation can provide better entries with
less certainty.

109
00:08:16,419 --> 00:08:21,960
Waiting for confirmation provides higher certainty
at the expense of a later entry.

110
00:08:21,960 --> 00:08:28,139
Let’s say you’re monitoring this specific
support level.

111
00:08:28,139 --> 00:08:34,649
Price is aggressively moving towards it and
closed in this area with a big momentum red

112
00:08:34,649 --> 00:08:36,200
candle.

113
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:41,779
You wanted to buy here, you patiently waited
for price to reach this area.

114
00:08:41,779 --> 00:08:45,959
But with this big red candle, do you enter?

115
00:08:45,959 --> 00:08:52,320
The risk to buy into a support level while
the market is in free fall is risky.

116
00:08:52,320 --> 00:08:57,800
But that's precisely why these trades offer
you great profit potential.

117
00:08:57,800 --> 00:09:03,150
You anticipated the move and you were rewarded
for the risk you took.

118
00:09:03,150 --> 00:09:07,510
The conservative traders would have waited
for a confirmation.

119
00:09:07,510 --> 00:09:11,170
They would have entered after a rejection
candle.

120
00:09:11,170 --> 00:09:15,090
But, they already missed the initial price
move.

121
00:09:15,090 --> 00:09:21,340
That move may be over …and those who took
the risk and bought at the support level are

122
00:09:21,340 --> 00:09:23,970
now potentially taking their profits.

123
00:09:23,970 --> 00:09:29,660
The point to consider is that whenever you
wait for confirmation you give up potential

124
00:09:29,660 --> 00:09:31,720
profits.

125
00:09:31,720 --> 00:09:36,070
And there’s the other side of the coin,
where price broke that support level with

126
00:09:36,070 --> 00:09:42,290
ease, and all traders anticipating a bounce
are now at a loss, while the conservative

127
00:09:42,290 --> 00:09:45,899
traders are the winners in this situation.

128
00:09:45,899 --> 00:09:52,740
Your job here is to find a good compromise
between getting in too early due to a signal

129
00:09:52,740 --> 00:09:59,700
coming from market noise and getting in too
late due to a signal that misses most of the

130
00:09:59,700 --> 00:10:00,700
opportunity.

131
00:10:00,700 --> 00:10:06,630
It’s a hard task, I know, and it will take
you some time to find the balance.

132
00:10:06,630 --> 00:10:10,519
But when you’ll find it, trading will become
a lot easier.

133
00:10:10,519 --> 00:10:17,029
A smaller stop loss doesn’t mean a smaller
risk

134
00:10:17,029 --> 00:10:22,700
You have a tool on your side to assist you
in giving trades the time they require to

135
00:10:22,700 --> 00:10:24,220
turn into winners.

136
00:10:24,220 --> 00:10:30,890
That tool is stop loss placement and more
specifically, using wider stop losses.

137
00:10:30,890 --> 00:10:36,899
Many traders are naturally tempted to place
a small stop loss on their trades.

138
00:10:36,899 --> 00:10:43,001
They think that a smaller stop loss distance
means a smaller risk, and that wider stop

139
00:10:43,001 --> 00:10:45,420
losses means they are risking more.

140
00:10:45,420 --> 00:10:51,639
But, it is obvious that it is the contract
size (or number of lots) that determines the

141
00:10:51,639 --> 00:10:56,010
risk per trade, not the stop loss distance.

142
00:10:56,010 --> 00:11:02,389
The stop loss distance is nowhere near as
important as the position size you are trading.

143
00:11:02,389 --> 00:11:10,510
The position size determines how much MONEY
is risked per trade, not the stop loss distance.

144
00:11:10,510 --> 00:11:15,380
The fact is many traders don’t take into
account market noise.

145
00:11:15,380 --> 00:11:22,190
Market noise is simply the price data that
distorts the picture of the current trend.

146
00:11:22,190 --> 00:11:25,390
This includes small corrections and intraday
volatility.

147
00:11:25,390 --> 00:11:32,110
You say you’re minimizing risk and use a
small stop loss, but you don’t take into

148
00:11:32,110 --> 00:11:36,540
account random price spikes that may occur.

149
00:11:36,540 --> 00:11:43,310
Giving a trade even another 30 pips for example,
can significantly improve the chances of that

150
00:11:43,310 --> 00:11:46,670
trade flipping from a loser to a winner.

151
00:11:46,670 --> 00:11:53,300
Ask yourself, what’s better: Placing 10
trades with small stops and losing on most

152
00:11:53,300 --> 00:12:00,720
of them or placing 2 trades with wide stops,
winning big on one and taking a loss on the

153
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:01,850
other?

154
00:12:01,850 --> 00:12:05,170
The second strategy is the one you should
follow.

155
00:12:05,170 --> 00:12:11,360
Remember, wider stops will keep you in the
game longer and improve your chances over

156
00:12:11,360 --> 00:12:13,209
a series of trades.

157
00:12:13,209 --> 00:12:19,430
Give the market the time to move in your favor

158
00:12:19,430 --> 00:12:24,020
Trades do not often turn out exactly as we
want them to.

159
00:12:24,020 --> 00:12:29,649
This affects our emotions because, we are
wired to want instant results.

160
00:12:29,649 --> 00:12:35,529
There’s a difference between what we expect
from a trade and what a trade actually gives

161
00:12:35,529 --> 00:12:36,529
us.

162
00:12:36,529 --> 00:12:44,040
A common mistake is to expect some unrealistically
big profit on nearly every trade you take.

163
00:12:44,040 --> 00:12:50,430
You are a day trader, but you place profit
targets that are 200 pips away from your entry.

164
00:12:50,430 --> 00:12:55,750
And then when this target doesn’t get hit,
you experience emotional pain and distress.

165
00:12:55,750 --> 00:12:58,810
And here’s another bad mindset.

166
00:12:58,810 --> 00:13:05,070
You often have unrealistic expectations of
how long a trade will take to play out.

167
00:13:05,070 --> 00:13:07,360
I’m also guilty of this.

168
00:13:07,360 --> 00:13:12,290
I want every trade I enter to immediately
go into profit territory.

169
00:13:12,290 --> 00:13:19,660
I’m mostly a swing trader now, and I would
love a 100 pip move in my favor in my first

170
00:13:19,660 --> 00:13:26,510
day, but if the average daily range is only
60 pips, what would be unrealistic.

171
00:13:26,510 --> 00:13:33,139
A trade can sometimes take several hours or
days to play out, depending on your time frame,

172
00:13:33,139 --> 00:13:38,432
and you need to keep this in mind because
you will never make money if you don’t give

173
00:13:38,432 --> 00:13:42,470
the market the time to move in your favor.

174
00:13:42,470 --> 00:13:47,600
Next time you place a trade, you should be
prepared to see it out and let it run for

175
00:13:47,600 --> 00:13:51,209
days or weeks if it needs to.

176
00:13:51,209 --> 00:13:56,810
If you’re a swing trader, don’t get scared
by an intra-day fluctuations against your

177
00:13:56,810 --> 00:14:02,880
position and don’t exit too early, as you
may miss out on a potentially strong trend

178
00:14:02,880 --> 00:14:03,880
move.

179
00:14:03,880 --> 00:14:09,540
It’s also very important that you understand
that each day and each week the market can

180
00:14:09,540 --> 00:14:17,160
only move so far, so don’t have unrealistic
expectations of how far your trade might move

181
00:14:17,160 --> 00:14:20,110
in a certain period of time.

182
00:14:20,110 --> 00:14:26,519
Now, these are only a part of the measures
I took to improve my trading.

183
00:14:26,519 --> 00:14:31,959
If you want to learn other tips and tricks
to be ahead of the game, make sure you watch

184
00:14:31,959 --> 00:14:32,959
this video.

185
00:14:32,959 --> 00:14:38,690
And also check out our academy program, if
you want to further level up your trading.

186
00:14:38,690 --> 00:14:39,769
Until next time.

